red CO<inf>2</inf> to enhance the production capacity by 50% via CO<inf>2</inf> hydrogenation. The process consists of two sections, biomass processing to syngas and its conversion to methanol, and the electrolytic section where hydrogen is produced to hydrogenate the CO<inf>2</inf> that has been captured during syngas cleaning. The integrated facility produces up to 207Mgal/yr of methanol and 318kt/yr of oxygen, but requires a large amount of electricity to generate the hydrogen. Thus, it can only be used in regions where wind velocity is above 8m/s and solar radiation is above 5kWh/m<sup>2</sup>/day such as in the Midwest of US, certain regions in China or in the South of Europe. The investment is high, around 1000M€, but the production cost of methanol is promising, 0.25-0.35€/kg with a high production capacity.</ce:para> </abstract></dc:description><link href="http://api.elsevier.com/content/abstract/scopus_id/85008168828" rel="self"/><link href="https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?partnerID=HzOxMe3b&amp;scp=85008168828&amp;origin=inward" rel="scopus"/><link href="https://www.scopus.com/inward/citedby.uri?partnerID=HzOxMe3b&amp;scp=85008168828&amp;origin=inward" rel="scopus-citedby"/></coredata><affiliation href="http://api.elsevier.com/content/affiliation/affiliation_id/60025028" id="60025028"><affilname>Universidad de Salamanca</affilname><affiliation-city>Salamanca</affiliation-city><affiliation-country>Spain</affiliation-country></affiliation><affiliation href="http://api.elsevier.com/content/affiliation/affiliation_id/60027950" id="60027950"><affilname>Carnegie Mellon University</affilname><affiliation-city>Pittsburgh</affiliation-city><affiliation-country>United States</affiliation-country></affiliation><authors><author auid="35307425700" seq="1"><ce:initials>M.</ce:initials><ce:indexed-name>Martin M.</ce:indexed-name><ce:surname>Martín</ce:surname><ce:given-name>Mariano</ce:given-name><preferred-name> <ce:initials>M.</ce:initials> <ce:indexed-name>Ma